1. Download and install docker
	after successful install run the below
			--launch powershell
						docker --version
						docker run --rm hello-world 
			you should see "Hello from Docker!" output. 

--launch powershell	
2. Create a project
			mkdir WDTech-API
			cd WDTech-API

	notepad app.py
	notepad app.py (this should open notepad authomatically)

paste this:

				from flask import Flask
				import datetime

				app = Flask(__name__)

				@app.route("/")
				def home():
					return "Welcome to WDTech API Test Test Testing!"
					
				@app.route("/health")
				def home():
					return {
						"status": "healthy",
						"timestamp": datetime.datetime.now().isoformat()
					}
					
				if __name__ == "__main__":
					app.run(host="0.0.0.0", port=5000)
	

save and close.

	create requirements.txt
	notepad requirements.txt (this should open notepad authomatically)
	
paste this:

                flask

save and close


3. Create Dockerfile
   notepad Dockerfile

paste this:

				FROM python:3.11-slim

				WORKDIR /app

				COPY requirements.txt .
				RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

				COPY . .

				EXPOSE 5000

				CMD ["python", "app.py"]


save and close


4. Build the Docker Image locally (still in powershell)

				docker build -t wdtech/api:1.0.0 .


Wait for build to finish


5. Tag it Appropriately (Semver)
Already tagged 1.0.0.
Add latest tag: 

				docker tag wdtech/api:1.0.0 wdtech/api:latest
				or
				docker tag wdtech/api:1.0.0 wdtech/api:1.0.1


6. Confirm Image was created Successfully

				docker images | findstr wdtech 

Should see:
			wdtech/api	1.0.0
			wdtech/api	latest or 1.0.1

Also inspect it:

		docker inspect wdtech/api:1.0.0


7. Run the Container Locally

		docker run -d --name wdtech-api -p 5000:5000 wdtech/api:1.0.0


8. Confirm It's Running

		docker ps -a

Should see: wdtech-api


9. Test It
		Open browser

        Type address: http://localhost:5000

You should see: 
		Welcome to WDTech API Test Test Testing!

Test health endpoint: 

        Type address: http:/localhost:5000/health

10. View logs

		docker logs wdtech-api

live logs:

		docker logs -f wdtech-api

11. Show Port Exposure

		docker port wdtech-api
		5000/tcp -> 0.0.0.0:5000

12. Demonstrate Debugging (Stop container)

		docker stop wdtech-api
		docker rm wdtech-api

	run interactively

		docker run --rm -it --endpoint sh wdtech-api:1.0.0

inside container:

	ls -la (should see files)

now break something:

	Edit app.py and remove this line:

	host="0.0.0.0"

change to 

	app.run(port=5000)

Rebuild 

	docker build -t wdtech/api:1.0.1 .


Run again:

	docker run -d --name wdtech-api -p 5000:5000 wdtech/api:1.0.1

Now try browser -> it wont work.


13. Debug 

	docker logs wdtech-api

You'll see it's binding to 127.0.0.1 only

Run interactively:

	docker run --rm it --entrypoint sh wdtech/api:1.0.1


Bash

	python app.py



How To Explain This Professionally

If someone asks:

“I created a sample WDTech API service, added a Dockerfile, built and tagged the image using semver (1.0.0), verified the image using docker images and inspect, ran the container exposing port 5000, validated via browser, and demonstrated log inspection and interactive debugging using an overridden entrypoint.”


What to SAY while demoing (short and senior-sounding)

“I’m using semver tags to keep releases reproducible: 1.0.0 and optionally latest for convenience.”

“I validate the image exists via docker images and docker inspect.”

“I run it with explicit port publishing -p host:container and validate via curl.”

“If it fails, first step is docker logs, then I run it interactively with an overridden entrypoint to debug inside the container.”
